            "contents":"You’ve all made some interesting deductions, but who is responsible for the crimes?\n\nFirstly, lets eliminate those who are not guilty by looking at each murder. Kat O’Wail was electrocuted in her bath with her own stereo.\n\nWe know that Kat wanted to stop the sale of the hotel going through because she would lose her job. So who stopped her plans?\n\nAl himself perhaps? If he thought that she may speak to Lotta Rooms and tell her something to stop her buying the hotel , then he might have wanted her out of the way. The tactics he used to buy the land and buildings for his hotel show us that he has few scruples. But Al was seen in the lounge at 1pm still schmoosing the guests as usual and as we also know that Kat was in her bath by 12.30pm and therefore dead very soon after, Al could not have done it.\n\nWhat about Kat’s support act, Wanda Limelight. Wanda hated living in Kat’s shadow and having little chance of being talent spotted. Wanda wanted the sale to go through, as it would get Kat out of her way. But Wanda does not have access to a hotel Master Key, and if Kat had invited her into her room, then why would she then go off and have a bath? No, Wanda had no opportunity to kill Kat.\n\nIvor Torch has a history of violence if the rumours are to be believed. If he knew of the affair between Al and Kat he might have killed her in a jealous rage. He does have a Master Key to her room. But at midnight Ivor didn’t see Kat because he was talking to a local police officer and then went straight to Al, by which time it was already 1am. So if Ivor was going to kill Kat, he was too late.\n\nWhat about the rival hotelier, Lotta Rooms? She’s wanted to get Al out of town for five years, so she may have not wanted Kat to convince Al otherwise, and her spy Iona Sheet could have already tipped her off about Kat’s feelings. However, Lotta was attending a conference and stayed in London last night. So she was well out of harm’s way.\n\nThe ambitious Stu Pots. Looking for a chance to shine, but his career blocked by another, in this case the Head Chef. He wanted the sale to go ahead because the Head Chef would leave and he would get promoted and be able to prove his worth to Lotta Rooms. Although he had access to a Master Key, he handed it over to Ivor Torch at 11pm. Kat was still on stage, so he had no access to the room at the time of the murder.\n\nThis leaves us with Iona Sheet, the Head Housekeeper. She knew of Kat’s feelings because of the gossiping Wanda Limelight. She also confronted her about it, and complained about the state of her room. She even admitted that she had cleaned it herself before, so she obviously has been in there before, and knew about the stereo in the bathroom. Iona wasn’t going to let a silly little blonde ruin everything for her. She let herself into Kat’s room and shoved the stereo into the bath, hoping it would look like an accident. If she hadn’t left in such a hurry, she may have got away with it.\nBut before I arrest Iona Sheet, there was another murder, that of Bill Due, the Chief Accountant.\n\nLotta Rooms has been in a relationship with Bill for a long time, and planted him in the hotel as spy from the beginning. He was the one who fed her the financial information she needed to buy the hotel. However, he also found information showing that she should not buy the hotel and simply wait for it to close. I don’t see any reason for Lotta Rooms to kill Bill.\n\nBill was seen arriving for work and going straight to his office at 8am. Both Al Mascarpone and Wanda Limelight were in the restaurant between 7.45am and 8.15pm, and then came straight to this meeting. So neither of them had any opportunity to kill the spying accountant.\n\nIona Sheet did see Bill before he died, but not to speak to. He raced past her on his way to his office. There’s no evidence that Iona had any idea that Bill was going to stop the sale, but even if she did, they were both spies for Lotta, and he would have