      {
        "label": "Rules Of The Game",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Rules Of The Game",
            "contents":"The Host's Word is Law: The Host is impartial. If you have a problem or want to do something unusual, see the Host. The Host's power is absolute, and cannot be affected by Abilities!\n\nWinning and Losing: You can achieve most of your goals simply by talking to people. The Host will announce when the game is over. If you haven't succeeded by that point ? you're too late! Be warned ? not everyone here will want you to succeed!\n\nDoing Stuff: Ordinary actions are resolved by simply carrying them out. If you want to try something unusual (such as swing from a chandelier), see the Host. The Host knows everything, and will be able to tell you the outcome of whatever it is that you are trying to do. (For example, the chandeliers may be too high to reach.) Do use your imagination, though! ? this is a very flexible game, and you can do all sorts of things beyond what's listed in these rules.\n\nFighting: 1884 was a rough, tough time in Cactus Gulch! Your character may wish to grapple with, come to blows with, or even stab or shoot one of the other characters. Should you wish to do something along these lines though, don't just dive in! See the Host first and tell them what you plan to do so they can oversee and give you more detailed rules if it's necessary.\n\nLeaving the town: Cactus Gulch is in the middle of nowhere and the surrounding territories can be quite hostile. You are therefore advised not to attempt leaving town during the course of the evening.\n\nItem Cards: Any items of importance within the game are represented as Item cards ? and the only items that can affect the game are those detailed on the cards. If you do not have an Item card, you do not have that item with you.\n\nTime: Way out West is played over three hours, with extra time for reading your character etc. There will be breaks to get drinks and food! The Host will keep track of the time for you."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Host's Timetable",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Host's Timetable",
            "contents":"The times below are our suggestions, but of course you may need to adapt them to your own timetable.\n\n7:00 to 7:30 Guests arrive\nAs your guests arrive, welcome them to the Silver Dollar Saloon and hand them their character envelopes. Sit them together in groups, corresponding with the groups on the cast list: so the Locals will all sit together in one area of the room, the Out-of-Towners will sit together in a separate corner, and the Natives will sit together. The idea of this is that they'll straight away be close to the other characters that they \"\"know\"\", and won't have to spend the first ten minutes wandering around gazing at people's name badges.\n\nGive them at least twenty minutes to read and digest their characters. (Twenty minutes is actually a bit short — particularly if you didn't send the characters out in advance.)",
            "titletip":"Are you the Host? Only host can see Host's Timetable."
          },
          {
            "title": "The game begins",
            "contents":"7:30 The game begins\nRead the Announcement: Zeke's Body out to the players. This starts the game!\n\n7:30 to 8:15 Begins in the Silver Dollar Saloon\nThis section of the evening is usually fairly quiet. Everyone should be talking to each other and sounding out their fellow players. There may be various pick-pocketing and other such activities going on that you will be asked to supervise.\n\nThere is a Scene of the Crime handout. Show it to anyone who wants to examine Zeke's body. At the end of this period, you should announce that the Stagecoach has arrived."
          },
          {
            "title": "The Stagecoach arrives",
            "contents":"8:15 The Stagecoach arrives\nThis serves as a break and gives your guests a chance to refresh their drinks or plates of food. You should hand the letter from Sheriff Goodright warning about Jake Calhoun to Deputy Dan. You should hand the skirt item card to Lucy and tell her it's from her friend Kate.\n\nAfter five minutes, you should announce that the telegraph system has been fixed and that anyone who wants to can ask you to send a telegram (Clem, Mel and one of the lawmen should definitely want to). Show them the telegram form. At the end of this period, you should announce at what time the Judgement will be delivered.\n\n8:15 to 9:00 Tension mounts and play continues in the Silver Dollar\nEarly on in this session, hand out the reply telegrams to anyone who has sent a telegram. By now characters will probably be using their abilities freely on each other, to try and find out who knows what and can help them achieve their goals. There may even be some sneaky attempts to harm one another. Remember though, no-one can die before the Judgement is delivered.\n\nDuring this period, it may be that Judge Paulson gets publicly discredited. If this should happen, either the Sheriff or the Deputy Sheriff will get the job of making the judgement: you should make sure that they know this, so they have time to think what they are going to say.\n\nAt the end of this period announce that Judgement is about to be delivered: if it's by one of the lawmen rather than the Judge, explain why."

          },
          {
            "title": "Judgement is delivered",
            "contents":"9:00 Judgement is deliveredThis may go either way — the land may be awarded to either Doc Faraday or Lucy Calhoun. When the Judge/Sheriff/Deputy Sheriff has finished, give the players a moment or two to react — then tell everyone that they have twenty minutes left to resolve any unfinished business.\n\nAnd announce that from this point onwards, people can be arrested. And, perhaps more importantly, people can be killed!\n\n9:10 to 10:00 Climax\nDuring this period people will probably be desperately trying to do final deals, find missing items or to take their revenge. Announce when there is five minutes left to go, and tell everyone to finish what they are trying to do. Read out the Announcement: End of the Game"

          },
          {
            "title": "Epilogue",
            "contents":"10:00 to 10:30 Epilogue\nAt the end of the evening, it's time to find out who killed Zeke, and what was really going on. Who killed Zeke? Get everyone settled down and relaxed. Ask each character in turn to say who they think killed Zeke Calhoun, how they did it, and how they know it was them.\n\nGive the handout entitled The Solution to Dan Fairweather. Have it read out to everyone. We usually have a debrief where everyone reveals their secrets and shares what went on. We have two ways of doing these — you can use whichever you prefer (but in general we use the first option with smaller games as it can take a long time with a lot of people).\n\nDebrief #1: Gather everyone together and ask them all to point to the person who they think was secretly related to Zeke ? but dont ask the real thief to own up just yet. You can also ask them to point to the person who they think cut Zekes ropes, the person who is a hired killer, and the person who was guilty of fraud back East. Then ask each player to explain who they were, what they were up to (now the guilty parties can own up, when it's their turn) and whether they succeeded or not.\n\nOnce everyone has had their say, then you can end the debrief and let everyone wind down and swap stories.\n\nDebrief #2: Gather everyone together and then the Host asks specific questions which the players would answer. For example:\n\nWho was secretly related to Zeke?\nWho cut Zeke's ropes?\nWho was a hired killer?\nWho was guilty of fraud back East?\nPlus any other questions that you want to know the answer to.\n\nOnce these questions have been answered, then open the floor for the players to ask any questions. It's likely that you won't be able to answer all of the questions ? so let the appropriate player answer. After a while, the questions will dry up and you can end the debrief and let everyone wind down and swap stories.\n\nPrizes\nYou might like to give out small prizes for most successful character, best costume, most enjoyable performance, best concealment of secret goals, or anything else you can think of that deserves rewarding! It's not essential, but it rounds the evening off nicely."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Host's Detailed Rules-1",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Host's Detailed Rules",
            "contents":"Your guests have the basic rules of the game included in their character booklets. Unfortunately, the Host needs a few more rules.It is advised that you get a piece of paper and write a summary of detailed rules.",
            "titletip":"Are you the Host? Only host can see Host's Detailed Rules."
          },
          {
            "title": "Abilities",
            "contents":"Everyone has abilities that allow him or her to do something special. For example, some characters have the Let's gossip! ability. If they follow the instructions on the card, they can make\nanother player show their Information in exchange for their own. At the same time, the other player might play a different ability back on them."

          },
          {
            "title": "Pickpocket",
            "contents":"The Pickpocket ability lets your players steal items from other characters. To use it, they simply show you the card (and cross off one use) and tell you what they want to steal, and from whom. You must then go to the victim, look through their Item cards, take that Item and give it to the thief. Try not to make it obvious who is the thief!\n\nNote that if the person wants to steal cash instead of an Item, then they can steal $50 (no more). If the victim doesn't have the requested Item (or cash) you should take something else, at random — unless they don't have anything, in which case the thievery attempt fails.\n\nIf the victim tries to play a Not So Fast! ability to prevent the thief, they can. (It doesn't say so explicitly on the card ? that's to avoid forewarning people that there are thieves about!) In this instance they have caught the thief in the act ? you should let your guests act out the consequences."

          },
          {
            "title": "Rock-Paper-Scissors",
            "contents":"Sometimes players want to do something that isn't covered by an ability card or the other rules. When that happens, challenge them to a round of Rock-Paper-Scissors. (Or, if they want to do something to someone, they must beat them at Rock-Paper-Scissors.) If what they are doing is relatively simple, let them succeed on a tie. For trickier actions, they fail on a tie. Use common sense to decide.\n\nIf someone wants to do something that is covered by an ability card, then they cannot do it without that ability. (For example, they Pickpocket can't try and pick pockets if they don't have the ability.)"

          },
          {
            "title": "Other Weird Stuff",
            "contents":"Players can sometimes stretch the limits of Way out West. When they try to do something wacky and weird, ask yourself two questions: \"\"Is it fun?\"\" and \"\"Will it upset the evening for everyone else?\"\"\n\nFor example, suppose things are going really badly for Blaise Sadler, who in a fit of pique decides to set fire to the Saloon. After all, that's bound to teach the townsfolk a lesson for looking down on her! So she approaches you with that suggestion. Well, while this may be fun for Blaise, burning the Saloon would definitely detract from the game for everyone else.\n\nRefusing such a suggestion can be done in two ways. You can either say ?No, you can't set light to the Saloon without everyone else seeing.? Or you can let Blaise start the fire and then raise the alarm, relying on the Cactus Gulch Voluntary Fire Department to put out the blaze. (And because you want them to succeed, they will.)"

          },
          {
            "title": "Make It Up!",
            "contents":"The secret to being a good Host is in knowing that your guests don't know what's right and what's wrong. So if in doubt — make something up! If it sounds right, it is right."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Host's Detailed Rules-2",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Fighting",
            "contents":"In this game, it's possible for characters to fight each other – infact, they probably will, once they've realized they're enemies. We handle fighting with some very simple rules:\n\nIn general, when one player wants to attack another, they must have a weapon Item card (ie. one which has \"\"(Weapon)\"\" written on it), must be within touching distance, and must succeed in a Rock-Paper-Scissors challenge against the intended victim.\n\nIf the attacker wins the challenge, the victim falls unconscious. (See Unconscious people, below.)\n\nIf it's a tie, or they lose the R-P-S challenge, then the attack missed and the defender gets to take an action:\n\nThey can attack back (if they have a weapon or an appropriate ability).\nThey can flee and can't be attacked again by this person for10 minutes.\nOr they can take some other action.\n\nThere are a few things that can affect this simple rule:\n\nWho goes first – in general, the person who declared that they were going to attack first, gets to attack first. In the rare case where characters all want to attack each other simultaneously, then you will have to decide (using a coin toss, for example) who attacks first.\n\nMultiple combat – if there are several people wanting to attack each other at the same time, or to defend each other, or anything more complicated, you have to decide who goes first. Each successive attack is carried out just as the above example.\n\nMethods of healing – healing is normally done with a First aid kit Item. After healing an injury, the player who has the Item used should check off one of the uses on the card.\n\nNote that if you dont want to have fighting in your game, either because you think its too complicated or because you dont want to be that bloodthirsty, you can just do without it altogether – and if players ask you how they can fight each other, just tell them that they cant. That works fine too.",
            "titletip":"Are you the Host? Only host can see Host's Detailed Rules."
          },
          {
            "title": "High Noon",
            "contents":"No Western would be complete without a gunfight! Sneaky, ornery  critters may just try to gun down their opponents in the saloon, but any true shootist will want to challenge their opponent to a fair fight. If any of the players wants to challenge another, you should give them the \"High Noon\" card so they can challenge their opponent to a duel out in the street outside the saloon. They then do three Rock-Paper-Scissors trials against each other – on each trial, the one who wins will wound the other. Note that if one of them has the Sharpshooting ability, they'll wound their opponent on a draw as well. If both have Sharpshooting, they'll both be wounded on a draw! So a duel like this can be quite bloody."
          },
          {
            "title": "Unconscious people",
            "contents":"After someone has been rendered unconscious, they should lie still. What follows then is:\n\nIf someone else heals them within ten minutes, theyimmediately make a full recovery.\n\nIf no-one heals them in ten minutes, and the injury occurred before the judgement, then after the ten minutes have passed, they recover fully and can rejoin the game.\n\nIf no-one heals them in ten minutes, and the injury occurred after the judgement, then the injury was fatal and after the ten minutes have passed they die. (See Death, below.) First Aid Kit\n\nHealing requires the item. Anyone can use it; they don't have to be medically qualified. They immediately restore the victim to health.\n\nPlayers arent allowed to attack an unconscious character (so they cant finish them off while they are helpless). There must always be ten minutes between unconsciousness and death to allow for the injured character to be healed. (This isnt strictly realistic, but it's very hard on the victim if they can just be polished off at will while unconscious.)Players will often ask if they can search unconscious people, steal their items and so on. They can, although of course if its in a public place, everyone else will see them doing so. You should look through the unconscious persons cards and give the searcher any Item cards and money included, so they can choose which they wish to take. Dont let them see their victims Abilities, Secret or Clue though!"

          },
          {
            "title": "Poison",
            "contents":"The Indians have poisonous seeds (Wawambe seeds) and Slick O'Hare also has Poison Pills. When a character poisons another, they will tell you, and you should then show the victim the You have been poisoned! card. Poison has the following effects:\n\nThe victim may not use any abilities.\n\nIf the victim cannot find an antidote, then they will die. The speed at which poison kills its victim is as follows:\n\nIf the poison is administered after the judgement, then it takes ten minutes before killing its victim.\n\nIf the poison is administered before the judgement, then it causes the loss of abilities right away; but does not take full effect until the judgement, at which point it takes ten more minutes before killing its victim.\n\nIf the game ends before the poison is due to act (i.e., the poison was administered within the last ten minutes of the game), then the victim survives. The poisoner should have acted sooner!\n\nPoison can only be healed with Yerba Buena seeds, which can only be administered by Three Feathers (or by Runs Like a Deer, if you aren 't using Three Feathers).\n\nA character can be poisoned (and treated) more than once."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Host's Detailed Rules-3",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Death",
            "contents":"Unfortunately, someone may well meet an untimely demise. To ensure that everyone has a good time, there is a No deaths before the judgement rule. If someone is garrotted or shot, it doesn't become lethal until then.\n\nThen, once they are definitely deceased, give them the With Your Last Dying Breath card to allow them one final, heroic action before slumping to the floor.\n\nDead characters can't reveal their secrets, information or abilities. The only things that may be taken from dead bodies are Item cards.\n\nIncidentally, it's not necessary for a character to be killed for Way out West to be a success. The real success is in how much everyone enjoys themselves.",
            "titletip":"Are you the Host? Only host can see Host's Detailed Rules."
          },
          {
            "title": " The Judgement",
            "contents":"Should be made by Judge Paulson an hour before the end of the game. If for any reason Judge Paulson has been discredited by then and is not able to make the judgement, this duty should be passed to Sheriff Blane (or, if he is not playing, Deputy Dan). Make it clear to whoever is giving the judgement that they have to decide one way or the other: the decision cannot be deferred."
          },
          {
            "title": "Arrest",
            "contents":"The Sheriff (and the Deputy) has the ability to arrest up to three characters: to do this, he tells the Host, crosses one use off his ability, and together he and the Host seat the arrested player in a central location of the Host's choosing. If more than one character is under arrest at one time, they must all be seated together. If a character is under arrest when the game is over, they may not leave Cactus Gulch and must stay there to await trial: all characters have the implicit goal of not being under arrest at the end of the game.\n\nOnce a player has been placed under arrest, the Sheriff may look through their items and confiscate any items that he suspects are evidence or otherwise related to a crime - but as a conscientious lawman, he would never take something for his own personal gain! As the Host, you may supervise this. Also, the Sheriff must show the Host some sort of evidence (items, testimony, or anything else he thinks convincing) as to why the arrested person has been arrested, or else they will automatically be released after 15 minutes (or within 5 minutes if before the judgement).\n\nWhen under arrest, characters cannot use any of their Abilities (apart from those which state otherwise).\n\nThe Sheriff may use one Arrest ability multiple times for the same character (should that character escape), but he may only arrest a total of three characters. He may revoke an arrest at any time, but that does not ?free up the arrest? to be used on someone else. Escaping from arrest is possible if:\n\nThe restrained player has outside help (who can cut the ropes or unlock the door, etc).\n\nThe restrained player comes up with a really good idea - and even then it may require a successful Rock-Paper-Scissors challenge with the Host.\n\nThe Quick Getaway ability may be used to free oneself, or another player may use it to free someone who is under arrest.\n\nThe Sheriff may himself free a player that he has arrested, but he does not gain that use back on his ability card."
          },
          {
            "title": " Silver lode maps",
            "contents":"There are four pieces of map in the game. Only two of them are genuine and make up the real map. Anyone asking you for help with this should be referred to Three Feathers, or (if Three Feathers is Ability not being used) Runs Like a Deer, who has the to tell if it's a real map."
          },
          {
            "title": "Money",
            "contents":"Most of the characters start of with some pocket change. These are small amounts, compared with the sums required for Fat Bull Range or Blaise's retirement fund. They're present to allow characters to pay each other for information or favours, or for any gambling anyone wants to do. If you think this will complicate things and confuse your players, you can leave the money out and it won't make any difference to the way the plots pan out."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Host's Guide to Plots",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Host's Guide to Plots",
            "contents":"This is a brief description of the plots running through Way out West. Once the evening starts the plots will become mixed up; but this is how they are at the start. ost of these plots will work themselves through in the hands of the layers, without you having to get too involved or answer questions.\n\nTimetable of events\nThe last few weeks:\nMid West Rail and South West Rail are competing o bring the railroad to Cactus Gulch. Both have been negotiating wth Zeke Calhoun, who owns the relevant land (Fat Bull Range). Mid West Rail will put the line through the Indian burial ground which lies on the range, as that's a shorter and cheaper route: South West Rail will go the long way around the burial ground.\n\nOne week ago:\nDoc Faraday and Zeke Calhoun played cards. Zeke lost Fat Bull Range to Doc. Doc may have been cheating, and there are marked cards around which may prove this. The game starts with Blaise Sadler, bordello madame, holding these cards.\n\nThe Silver Mine:\nZeke discovered a new silver lode, whose location is secret. He has made a map to it, half of which is with his daughter Lucy and half with Dan Fairweather. He has also made a fake map, which looks plausible, but an expert can detect it as valueless. Zeke gave half of this fake map to Blaise and half to his brother Jake/Elijah. The four half-maps can be joined in any combination of pairs, but only if the halves including Three Fingers Rock and Dead Dog Ravine are put together can the mine be found.\n\nThe mine is on land that is currently unclaimed, so having the map does not give the owner the right to exploit it (unless they wish to do so secretly and illegally). But when at some future point that area of the mountains comes up for claiming, the owner of the map will be able to claim the portion where the lode is, and they will then be able to own and operate a mine there. So having the full correct map is tremendously valuable.\n\nThe Judgement:\nJudge Paulson must decide tonight who owns the land following the card game. He is being blackmailed by Clem Parham of Mid West Rail, who has knowledge of the Judge's shady past.\n\nZeke's death:\nZeke succumbed to a heart attack while tied up and after having been beaten up by Clem and Slick / Saul. Although a modern jury might consider this to be manslaughter, in the old West at least one of them will be considered guilty of his murder, and due some brisk and permanent justice if the case can be proved against them.",
            "titletip":"Are you the Host? Only host can see Host's Guide to Plots."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Zeke's Body",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Zeke's Body",
            "contents":"[To be read out by the Host.]\nFolks, I'm sorry to stop the celebrations but I have some real bad news to tell you. Pete the Stable Boy has just found Zeke Calhoun lying in the stable, and I'm afraid to say... He's dead!\n\nLooks like he'd been in some sort of fight and got a bad blow to the head. Also looks as if his hands were tied, but the rope has already been cut. One other strange thing, the top pocket of his shirt had been cut open — there ain't nothing inside.\n\nI can't tell you what the cause of death was yet, there are no signs of shooting or strangling or that the blow on the head was enough to kill him. Folks, no-one is to leave town until this mystery has been solved.",
            "titletip":"Ready to start? (You need hosts permission to read this announcement to start the game)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "label": "Scene of the Crime",
        "plots": [
          {
            "title": "Scene of the Crime",
            "contents":"The body of Zeke Calhoun is slumped in a corner of the stables, out of sight of the door. He is battered about the face and body, with a bad bruise to the left temple. His wrists are chafed and reddened and in an awkward position behind his back, as though they have been tied together. On the ground nearby are some short lengths of rope, cut with a sharp knife. A toppled chair is nearby.\n\nThe top pocket of Zeke's plaid shirt has been cut open and is flapping empty. Apart from that his pockets contain the usual sorts of things, and do not appear to have been searched.\n\nThere are no signs of shooting, stabbing or strangling. It does not look as though the blow on the head was enough to kill him."

